  "task": "# Relay stage 2: Research\nTask: recognize-new-tasks-for-run-all\nWorking directory: /tmp/nix-shell.ZPB9Bm/visual-relay/wt/fbb5c78605a5/plan-20260630194022/recognize-new-tasks-for-run-all\n\n## Task input\n# Recognize New Tasks for \"Run All\"\n\nWhen someone clicks \"Run All\", all of the tasks are indeed processed. However, that is just all the tasks that existed at the time that button was clicked.\n\nIf new tasks are created while a run is happening, those new tasks are not included in the run. They ought to be. However, to give the person time to make edits to new tasks (such as including attachments), those new tasks shouldn't be touched until the current batch is fully processed. That is especially important with a \"Standard\" run all given that allows for parallel processing of tasks. For the \"Sequential\" run all, it would naturally wait for the existing tasks to be processed before the new one is processed.\n\nIf someone decides to reorder a new task during a \"Sequential\" run all, that task should be processed in the chosen order rather than waiting for the full existing batch to complete.\n\n## Manifest\n(not set yet)\n\n## Prior stages\n## Stage 1 - Ideate\n\n{\n  \"summary\": \"New tasks created during a 'Run All' execution are currently excluded. They should be recognized and eventually processed \u2014 Standard mode processes them after the current batch completes; Sequential mode picks them up at task boundaries, honoring any reorder the user applied. Three approaches: (A) phased batches that auto-start a new batch after the current one finishes, (B) a rolling queue with a cooldown/deferred-enqueue for new tasks, (C) an event-driven pending set checked at natural boundaries.\",\n  \"options\": [\n    \"Option A: Checkpoint Batches \u2014 snapshot the task list as Batch N, process it fully, then auto-start Batch N+1 with any new tasks. Sequential reordering promotes a reordered task into the next batch at its new position.\",\n    \"Option B: Rolling Queue with Deferred Enqueue \u2014 stage new tasks with a cooldown timer; merge staged tasks into the queue at task-completion boundaries. Sequential reordering sets future queue insertion order.\",\n    \"Option C: Event-Driven Polling + Pending Queue \u2014 maintain a Pending Set of new tasks; runner checks it at natural boundaries (task end in Sequential, batch end in Standard). Sequential reordering assigns a priority index for sorted merge.\"\n  ]\n}\n\n\n\nEnd your reply with a single fenced ```json block, nothing after it, matching: { \"findings\": string, \"constraints\": string[] }",
