    "answer": "Here is my full research report:\n\n## Findings\n\n**Current architecture** (`RelayQueueController.DrainAsync`, line 115):\nAt the start of a drain, the task list is snapshotted via `var queue = Tasks.ToList()`. This snapshot is never re-examined \u2014 tasks created while the drain runs are invisible to it. There is already a test (`DrainAsync_TaskAddedMidRun_IsNotRunByCurrentDrainButRemainsForNext`) that explicitly validates this as the **current** (intended) behavior.\n\n**Task-creation during a drain is possible**: `CanCreateNewTask()` does not check `IsBusy` (line 284 of `Authoring.cs`), so the \"New Task\" dialog remains operable during a drain. Creating a task calls `ReloadTaskListAsync(slug)` which replaces the **GUI** `Tasks` collection (ObservableCollection\\<TaskRowViewModel\\>) \u2014 but **not** the controller's `Tasks` collection (ObservableCollection\\<RelayTaskItem\\>), which was populated by `RefreshAsync()` before the drain began.\n\n**Two-phase execution**:\n- **Standard mode** (default): Phase 1 runs planning stages (1\u20134) in parallel worktrees (bounded by `MaxPlanConcurrency`); Phase 2 runs execution stages (5\u201311) serially.\n- **Sequential mode**: Skips Phase 1 entirely; runs all stages serially per task in a single loop.\n\n**Reordering infrastructure**: Both the GUI (`MoveTask` \u2192 `TaskOrderStore.Save(...)`) and the controller (`MoveUp`/`MoveDown`/`ApplyOrder`) support reordering. The controller's `Tasks` collection can be reordered at any time (it's an `ObservableCollection`). The snapshot `queue = Tasks.ToList()` currently prevents reordering from affecting the in-flight run.\n\n**Pause support**: `_pauseRequested` is checked at the top of each Phase-2 loop iteration. When set, the drain returns early with partial results.\n\n**Circuit breaker**: `DrainCircuitBreaker` halts after 2 consecutive commit rejects or 3 consecutive flags (any type), writing a `DRAIN-HALTED` marker.\n\n**Queue state machine** (`RelayQueueState`): Idle \u2192 Refreshing \u2192 Running \u2192 (PauseRequested \u2192 Paused | ReviewNeeded | Completed | Failed).\n\n**Task lifecycle during drain**: Completed tasks are removed from the controller's `Tasks` list (line 225). Flagged tasks are removed then re-added with `NeedsReview = true` (line 245). The `DrainLifecycleCallbacks` hook `OnExecuteCompleted` fires for each task \u2014 the GUI uses it to reconcile archived rows (`ReconcileArchivedTaskRow`).\n\n**Relevant existing tests**:\n- `DrainAsync_TaskAddedMidRun_IsNotRunByCurrentDrainButRemainsForNext` \u2014 proves the current exclusion policy.\n- `DrainAsync_InterleavedRefreshDoesNotChangeOrderOrDuplicate` \u2014 proves a mid-drain `RefreshAsync()` doesn't affect the snapshot order.\n- `DrainAsync_UsesManualOrderAndPausesAtTaskBoundary` \u2014 proves reordering + pause-at-boundary work.\n\n## Constraints\n\n```json\n{\n  \"findings\": \"The RelayQueueController.DrainAsync snapshots the task list at start (var queue = Tasks.ToList(), line 115) and never re-examines it. New tasks created during a drain (CreateNewTaskAsync writes to disk and calls ReloadTaskListAsync for the GUI collection only) are invisible to the running drain. The controller's own Tasks ObservableCollection is separate from the GUI's Tasks collection \u2014 they're in sync only via RefreshAsync() before the drain. Sequential mode skips Phase 1 entirely (no parallel planning) and iterates one task at a time. Standard mode does parallel planning (Phase 1) then serial execution (Phase 2). Reordering is supported at the GUI level (via TaskOrderStore) and controller level (MoveUp/MoveDown/ApplyOrder) but the snapshot prevents mid-drain reorders from taking effect. Pause is checked at each Phase-2 loop top. The circuit breaker can halt on consecutive failures. Lifecycle callbacks (DrainLifecycleCallbacks) fire at plan-start/plan-done/execute-start/execute-done boundaries. The existing test DrainAsync_TaskAddedMidRun_IsNotRunByCurrentDrainButRemainsForNext explicitly validates the current exclusion behavior.\",\n  \"constraints\": [\n    \"New tasks must not be picked up mid-batch \u2014 they must wait until the current snapshot's tasks are fully processed (Standard) or at task boundaries (Sequential), to give the user time to edit content/add attachments.\",\n    \"Sequential mode must honor user reordering of new tasks: a reordered task should be processed at its new position, not forced to wait for the full original batch to complete.\",\n    \"Standard mode's parallel Phase 1 cannot be interrupted \u2014 new tasks must wait until the entire Phase 1 + Phase 2 cycle finishes before being considered.\",\n    \"The snapshot-based isolation (var queue = Tasks.ToList()) must be replaced or augmented without introducing race conditions from concurrent task creation/renaming/deletion.\",\n    \"The circuit breaker halt (consecutive failures) must still apply \u2014 new tasks discovered after a halt should run on the next drain, not be carried over into a halted run.\",\n    \"Pause/resume semantics must remain correct: pausing at a task boundary should not skip newly discovered tasks; resuming should eventually include them.\",\n    \"The controller's Tasks ObservableCollection is the source of truth for what to run \u2014 any new-task detection must reconcile with this collection rather than the GUI's TaskRowViewModel list.\",\n    \"Phase 1 (parallel planning) and Phase 2 (serial execution) have different lifecycle callbacks (plan vs execute) \u2014 new-task lifecycle events need a consistent integration point.\",\n    \"ArchiveOnDone moves committed task specs out of llm-tasks/; new tasks are created in llm-tasks/ \u2014 directory-watching or periodic refresh is needed to detect new files on disk during a drain.\",\n    \"The DrainSummaryLog (per-runId .log file) records all milestones \u2014 new-task tracking must not pollute this existing log format or duplicate entries.\",\n    \"Existing tests (especially DrainAsync_TaskAddedMidRun_IsNotRunByCurrentDrainButRemainsForNext and DrainAsync_InterleavedRefreshDoesNotChangeOrderOrDuplicate) must be updated to reflect the new behavior, or new tests added alongside them.\"\n  ]\n}\n```",
